Windows Registry Forensics (Clean Notes)

1. Accessing the Registry

Online (Live System)

Use regedit.exe
	•	HKEY_CURRENT_USER (HKCU)
Current logged-in user’s settings (preferences, recent activity, software configs)
	•	HKEY_USERS (HKU)
Contains all user profiles loaded on the system
(includes HKCU as a subset)
	•	HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE (HKLM)
System-wide configuration (hardware, OS, installed software)
	•	HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT (HKCR)
File associations and COM objects
Combined view of:
	•	HKLM\Software\Classes (system-wide)
	•	HKCU\Software\Classes (user-specific)
Priority: HKCU overrides HKLM
	•	HKEY_CURRENT_CONFIG (HKCC)
Current hardware profile (derived from SYSTEM hive)

⸻

2. Offline Registry Hives

Location:
C:\Windows\System32\Config\

Hive File	Mounted As	Description
DEFAULT	HKU.DEFAULT	Default user profile (logon screen settings)
SAM	HKLM\SAM	User accounts & password hashes
SECURITY	HKLM\SECURITY	Local security policies
SOFTWARE	HKLM\SOFTWARE	Installed applications & OS config
SYSTEM	HKLM\SYSTEM	Boot config, services, drivers


⸻

3. User-Specific Hives

Location:
C:\Users\<username>\
	•	NTUSER.DAT
→ Mounted as HKCU when user logs in
→ Contains user activity, MRUs, preferences
	•	USRCLASS.DAT
→ Mounted as HKCU\Software\Classes
→ Path:
C:\Users\<username>\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\
→ Stores file associations & shell info

Note: Both are hidden files.

⸻

4. AmCache Hive (Execution Artifacts)

Location:
C:\Windows\AppCompat\Programs\Amcache.hve
	•	Stores metadata about executed programs
	•	Includes:
	•	File paths
	•	Execution timestamps
	•	SHA1 hashes (partial)
	•	Useful for program execution evidence, even if deleted

⸻

5. Transaction Logs

Files:
	•	.LOG
	•	.LOG1
	•	.LOG2

Location:
C:\Windows\System32\Config\
	•	Act as a journal of registry changes
	•	May contain recent changes not yet committed
	•	Important for timeline reconstruction

Example:
	•	SYSTEM.LOG1
	•	SOFTWARE.LOG2

⸻

6. Registry Backups (RegBack)

Location:
C:\Windows\System32\Config\RegBack\
	•	Backup copies of registry hives
	•	Represent older system states
	•	Useful for:
	•	Recovering deleted keys
	•	Comparing historical changes

Important Note:
On newer Windows versions (Windows 10 1803+), RegBack may be disabled by default (files may be 0 KB unless manually enabled).

⸻

7. Key Forensic Insight
	•	Transaction Logs → Recent activity (volatile changes)
	•	Active Hives → Current state
	•	RegBack → Historical state

👉 Combine all three for full timeline reconstruction.

⸻

8. Quick Forensic Tips
	•	Always work on copies, never original hives
	•	Use tools:
	•	Registry Explorer (Eric Zimmerman)
	•	RegRipper
	•	Autopsy
	•	Focus on:
	•	Run / RunOnce keys (persistence)
	•	RecentDocs, TypedPaths (user activity)
	•	Services & Drivers (SYSTEM hive)
	•	Installed software (SOFTWARE hive)

